WonderInd: At Vienna I had the opportunity to see the painting of The Kiss by Klimt, one of my favorite art pieces in the world. With my brother, we prepared ourselves to see this painting as we both were excited to see this magnificent art piece we both loved.  So as soon as we entered the room in which the painting was exposed, we decided to close our eyes and take a deep breath before opening them, at this time we were excited, my heart was beating and I couldn’t hear or smell anything due to the excitement of seeing the painting in real life. As soon as we opened our eyes, my heart was beating fast and my senses were delighted, I couldn’t believe how beautiful it was, I didn’t wanted to stop staring at it. After a few minutes I looked at my brother and we had a laughter attack (I still can’t explain why). We laughed for about 5 minutes While staring at the painting. We still remember this moment very vividly

NeutralInd:
On Monday, we took up once again our family's new habit of hiking in the surrounding parks and hills as an escape from the house unded quarantine.  We have only this year discovered one of several county parks that make up much of east county in San Diego.  This one, in Bonita, encompasses a large reservoir and such bodies of water are welcome in semi-arid southern California.  But of course, we do have the ocean and magnificent beaches aplenty.  So, I had not slept well and was generally feeling grumpy yet welcomed the experience as I knew from many a past hike and, I might add, from many a morning when I have awoken feeling as though the bottom has fallen out of my world and that a monkey spent the night in my mouth....only to see the day turn on with the practice of yoga and the company of energetic, creative young people.  Now I have a happy, chirpy, busy four year old who never fails to light up the day with her natural joy and curiosity.

To access the trail, we generally park by horse boarding stalls, and the residents exhibited a curiosity around our arrival.  Since we're not permitted to pet them nor to feed them treats, that level of communication is denied, none the less we greeted one another in appropriate fashion.  I took it as an opportunity to practice my horse voice.  They are very forgiving of clumsy speech. The first part of this path requires a steep climb up to a bridge built for horses and their riders and my daughter, Sedona, was in a lazy clingy mood so opted for Daddy's shoulders or Shank's Pony as we used to call it.  I don't complain as her joy and trusting love enegize me and besides, the gyms have been closed since March.  Her aquisitive nature is awakened at the sight of snails clinging to dry stalks.  We are delayed briefly by her demands to drive back to the house and fetch her bug box, but finally convince her to collect the snails in her yellow beach bucket. 

 Sadly, the lush green of our short but generous rainy season has all faded to the typical crunchy golden brown, so if one fails to look deeply, it can all feel dreary.  None the less, the breeze was cool and little wonders appear at every turn.  We were carrying the only kite I could find on furtive visits to the local stores.  It's a cartoon version of a gawky looking flamingo with nobby knees on roller skates.  We have dubbed it "Mingo" and encourage it's awkward attempts at flight with shouts of "FLY MINGO!"  Sedona, the four year old, adds, "Come on, you can do it!"  So I am constantly testing the wind and observing how viorously the flags are flapping as we pass through the campground.  Rounding a rise through rough stubble and brush, the lake finally comes into view, and in that, I find enormous comfort and tranquility.  

We stroll to our favorite grassy spot on a hillside breathing in the beauty.  I notice that the tiny pink flowers have mostly dried up and am glad for the one bunch we carried home and preserved in a vase for weeks.  Aircraft coasting into San Diego airport drift in at regular intervals.  We munch on snacks and gulp down ice water and juice.  This is an ordinary, extraordinary moment in a day not quite normal at all because school is out, it is summer and because of Covid and the presence of masked surgeons even on these remote trails.  

The kite flys, the kite falls and the string gets tangled in one unholy knot.  I finally grasp what sailors have known for generations.  There is a windward side and a leeward side to this mountain and thus Mingo flops and flounders more than he flies.  My patience is almost exhausted once I finally unravel this mess, but then we ascend to the highest point of this hill and the kite finally leaps into the sky challenging the aircraft and OH MY, a par of young hawks!  More curious than threatened it seems, they cruise in to examine this weird pink bird, then jostling with one another continue their ceaseless drifting and diving, floating effortlessly as they hunt for bunnies and mice. "Do they eat snails? " I ask Sedona and kinda hope they will pick off the rattlesnake spotted on our last outing.

AweReflection:
J’étais dans le désert en Oman avec ma famille, après une très courte nuit nous nous sommes réveillés avant le lever du soleil pour aller l’admirer en haut des dunes. Lorsqu’il est apparu, la lumière a inondé ce désert si calme et si vaste et j’ai pris entièrement conscience de la marche du temps. Cette marche qui n’attend pas l’Homme, cette marche que l’on essaie de dépasser en courant le plus vite possible mais qui nous devance inexorablement. Combien de fois le soleil s’est-il levé sur ce désert avant que je ne le voie et combien de fois se lèvera-t-il apres mon passage ?
Je pense que ce fut la première fois de ma vie où je me suis rendu compte que le genre humain avait oublié l’humilité lors de son développement et moi le premier.
 Aussi beau ce spectacle fut il devint source de grande réflexion durant le reste de mon séjour, je restais des heures a fixer le plafond de ma chambre d’hôtel avec une boule au ventre inexplicable et inhabituelle.

AweReflection:
Je voyageais deux mois au Japon pour lâcher mon quotidien et en savoir plus sur moi.

Vers la fin de mon voyage, j'ai passé la nuit au bord d'un lac, et réveillé tôt, j'ai vu une immense montagne, cachée la veille par les nuages, elle était rougie et rosée par la brume et le soleil levant.

Plus la chaleur du matin d'été gagnait mon corps, plus la couleur si frappante que j'avais vu sur cette montagne s'estompait.

J'avais conscience de l'aspect éphémère dans chaque chose, mais cela m'a plus travaillé que les autres fois, d'une part parce que j'avais l'impression que mon voyage était passé si vite et parce que j'avais l'impression de ne rien avoir trouvé de littéralement transcendant ou mystique, comme on pourrait l'imaginer.

J'ai compris que mon chemin venait de commencer et que j'avais trouvé une sorte de carte intérieure qui me guiderait au long de mon existence.

WonderInd:
Several years ago , while visiting the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City, I was quite unexpectedly overcome by total sense of ecstasy (Joyful excitement or happiness mixed with a sense of deja vu).
My usual plan when entering a museum with many large collections is to head for the contemporary visual art areas, beginning with sculpture in various media and then architecture before going into galleries filled with art historical objects of ancient cultures.  But for no reason this time I almost floated into the galleries of large stone carvings of actual architectural details from ancient ruin sites in Mesopotamia.  Passing along tall pillars and massive arch fragments the space seemed to Open Up (as if in a choreographed program) to a larger than life size stone figure of a lion with the human head representing a king of Sumeria.  I stopped, transfixed and transported, feeling "goose bumps" on my arms and neck, tears poured down my cheeks while I stood in what seemed a time warp examining the the details of the stylized stone curls of the figure's shoulder length hair and beard.  At that moment I was sure that I had "been there before", in the sculpture's original location.  It sounds crazy, but I felt like "coming home to where I belonged".  After several minutes, I snapped out of the spell, self consciously wiped my tears and moved into the next galley space to recover.  However, it was not over!  I felt I needed to return to the Sumerian king's presence again, so I went back into the gallery where I had been overcome, and almost as intensely re-experienced the complete feeling of connectedness through time and place.
A few years later I visited the museum at Yale University to see an ancient stone fragment of Hammurabi's code and then nearby discovered another, seemingly smaller
Sumerian lion/king figure and upon recognition, again felt completely in awe and transported.

WonderInd: Je prends le temps de marcher pas loin de la maison, je constate qu.il n’y a pas beaucoup d.arbres à proximité. Je marche avec plaisir contemplant la végétation  même si je sais que les champs qui bordent la route sont couverts de pesticide. Je le regrette, mais la beauté de la nature reste apparente, je me pose la question : avant que les routes soient tracées et que les champs soient entretenus, il y avait quoi, des herbes folles partout... ce ne devait pas être facile de se déplacer... je pousse ma marche un peu plus loin que d.habitude, le temps est plaisant et nous avons eu de la pluie toute les dernières semaines, je profite de ce moment ensoleillé. Puis à la sortie d.un village , je trouve un arbre en bordure de route, je le contemple, l.admire et lui demande de m.accueillir, c"est un protocole que j.ai lu. Je m.approche de l.arbre et pose mes mains dessus. Tout simplement, le tronc est rugueux traversé de longues nervures profondes et sombres, j.approche mon corps de cet arbre et je savoure ce contact chaud. Est-ce qu je communique avec lui, oui, je le pense et ce que je vis dans ces moments là échappe sans doute au langage courant, les mots ne remplace pas l.expérience comme vous le savez. Je suis juste un peu dérangée par les maisons à proximité, mon attitude non conventionnelle pourrait-être remarquée mais sur je garde ma posture d.enlacement un bon moment avant de remercier cet arbre qui est généreux avec moi.

AweReflection:
I experienced feeling the human existence at its core, I would say the best visual representation would be https://tellusdmsmedia.newmindmedia.com/wsimgs/Vigelandsparken_skulptur__c_VisitOSLO_Thomas-Johannessen_2025826394.jpg

I felt that human life is imprisoned by the biological limitations of our body, and that different to animals we are to a certain degree conscious of this, but mostly unconscious. Mostly unconscious, because the pain of being aware of these limitations is quite strong. I did feel a strong pain and sadness while feeling this existence. But the pain transformed into sadness and then finally into a very strong sense of empathy and compassion of human kind. I could see how much human kind struggle to be more than human in so many activities. I saw and listened to some orchestral symphonies which brought me into tears. It brought me very warm feelings to see how we battle everyday life and take our time to produce this magical and superhuman symphonies in order for some moments to get closer to the divine or some goal that exceeds our limitations. I also reflected about how everyone is blind, our limitations become our center of attention, and our lives almost center around this limitations - or how to protect ourselves from these limitations. Eventually this focus on ourselves and our flaws, makes us blind towards other people's problems - and I felt that this understanding - that everyone is trying their best under their circumstances and human limitations, is the key for compassion.

Feedback: I would say that experience of awe might be followed by wonder. So that awe can be painful and sad and very arousing, before it transforms into a more calm state of wonder and happiness

WonderInd: Il y a beaucoup de choses qui m'ont émerveillé au cours de ma vie, les plus incroyables et inoubliables sont sans doute mes rencontres avec des animaux sauvages, que soient de simples lapins de garennes, de petites chauves souris, d'innombrables chevreuils ou encore lorsque j'ai nagé avec des dauphins sauvages à Mayotte et même approché une baleine à bosse. A chaque fois je me sens excité, tous mes sens sont en éveil je suis focalisé sur l'attitude des animaux , j'essaye d'analyser ce qu'ils sont en train de faire , d'où ils viennent, où ils vont. Ce qui me plait aussi, c'est de partager ces moments avec ma femme et mes enfants, nous partons tous les 5 soit à l'aube soit à l'aurore et nous sommes heureux et quoi que nous voyons cela devient extraordinaire.

WonderInd:
Il y a deux ans, je me suis retrouvée seule pour un voyage d'un mois au Kirghizistan. J'ai pris mon billet d'avion une semaine avant le départ, et en arrivant dans ce pays dont je ne connaissais à peu près que le nom, je me suis demandée ce que je faisais là. Puis très vite j'ai fait des rencontres, notamment celle d'une autre française de dix ans de plus que moi qui faisait le tour du monde depuis plusieurs année. 
Pendant quelques jours, nous avons voyagé à cheval avec un guide kirghiz de 18 ans, et avons passé l'une des nuits dans la yourte de sa famille, avec notamment ses trois petites nièces de 4 mois, 3 ans et 9 ans. Gulnara, Anara et Janara.
Les kirghiz parlant pas ou peu anglais, particulièrement dans les terres isolées, nous n'avions aucun moyen de communiquer. Mais nous avons passé 24h avec cette famille et vécu une grande complicité notamment avec la petite fille de 3 ans, Anara, avec laquelle nous avons joué au football, couru, été chercher de l'eau au lac, joué avec leur chien.
J'ai filmé Anara pendant une minute environ, elle regardait fixement l'objectif avec un grand sourire, elle riait, elle dansait. C'était un moment magique. L'universalité du rire et de la danse, au milieu des montagnes kirghizes.
